value:
Jared, I want to work with you because you've supported me in targeting my technical ZPD more than anyone else has so far.

I have a slight ambivalence about the issue of unclear communication as brought up this morning: on one hand, I totally believe in that "jump right in the deep end" philosophy, and that's where I'm happiest from a technical/flow standpoint. On the other hand, the more explicit the communication, the fewer spoons it takes me to process it, and I have to manage my spoons pretty carefully. And I recognize that not everyone is able to stay down in their ZPD by jumping in the deep end.

So in the end I personally feel like it's a good thing, and contributes to putting Trossello at somewhat of a higher difficulty level than Floworky.

I'd want to work with you more if you put a little more effort into clarifying the issues and desired features for Trossello, but take that with the caveat that all the cross-group collaboration is the particular thing that got me into my ZPD.

question:

"{{subject}}, I want to work with you because... and I would want to work with you more if..."
subject: Aileen Santos
value:
Hi Aileen! Thank you for the effort you put into this team while you struggled through your grief and loss—I know that it took a lot of effort to make it in, and I was impressed at how you showed up and contributed throughout all of that. 

I really appreciated how you and I framed the week, shared our learning styles, and requests of each other. It was helpful for when we were working together, and also awesome to see that model so I can use it in future teams. Awesome intentionality, and cool that you took notes on what we shared.

I experienced a physical inner tension during points when we disagreed on how to proceed. I don’t have much clarity on the potential reasons for this; wondering if it’s related to having been on a previous group in which you and Syd had major conflict (and my own aversion to conflict), or if it’s related to knowing that you’re going through major grieving, and me being concerned about conflict while you’re dealing with that.
Not a big thing, just wanted to name it, and I’m happy to chat about it if it’s helpful.

You're an excellent developer, a big contributor to our culture, and I look forward to working with you in the future.

subject: Stephan Weber
value:
I would like to work with you again because you bring a sense of comfortability to the team. You allowed for the perfect balance of breaks and work, never going too far off course, but still appreciating the need for restorative breaks to recuperate one’s mind. Working with you, I felt it easy to do some self-study and consistantly bounce from coordinating our project effort to performing our individual tasks, and then bringing it back again.
I felt like you were real and authentic, and I appreciate that you didn’t judge me when I brought myself to the table.
You honored our agency when you allowed me to work on my own SQL zoo problems while you worked on your own, and when I was having trouble, you offered to help without outright butting in (i.e. using your own solution and method); that is, you helped me come to the solution with the method I had already laid out.

value:
Ana, it's been a great week, and I think we've really put all that we've been reflecting on from last week into practice. I want to work with you because of the incredible amount of growth that's happened on both sides. I think it's true that our similarity has that mirror effect, and while it causes a LOT of tension sometimes, I've always come away from reflecting or seeking feedback on those tensions feeling like I have a lot more insight in how to just plain get better. So when I get away from my triggered lizard brain, I'm perfectly happy dealing with those tensions in the moment, because I know it means that I'm about to level up.

I'd want to work with you more if we were collectively better equipped to step out of those moments of friction before they affect us too deeply, but take that with a grain of salt, because I still recognize that every time it happens we get closer to that point. :)
